{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Distributional Hypothesis"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Distributional semantics is the study of meaning derived from patterns of word co-occurrence. Its foundational claim — the distributional hypothesis — was stated by J.R. Firth in 1957: "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "\"You shall know a word by the company it keeps.\""}, {"type": "text", "text": " Words that appear in similar contexts share similar meanings. \"Cat\" and \"dog\" both appear near \"pet\", \"food\", \"fur\", and \"vet\" — so they end up close together in any vector space built from context statistics."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This idea predates neural networks entirely. Count-based distributional methods — building a word-by-context matrix and then reducing it — were competitive with early neural word embeddings and directly inspired the design of GloVe."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Three-panel diagram: raw co-occurrence count matrix for 'bank' and 'cat'; PPMI-transformed matrix; SVD decomposition V×V ≈ (V×d)(d×d)(d×V) producing dense word vectors. Bottom: the distributional hypothesis quote."}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Co-occurrence Matrix"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Given a corpus, fix a context window of size "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "k"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". For every pair of words ("}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "i"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "j"}, {"type": "text", "text": "), count how many times "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "j"}, {"type": "text", "text": " appears within "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "k"}, {"type": "text", "text": " positions of "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "i"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". The result is a V×V matrix where V is the vocabulary size."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from collections import defaultdict\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef build_cooccurrence(sentences, vocab, window=2):\n    word2idx = {w: i for i, w in enumerate(vocab)}\n    V = len(vocab)\n    matrix = np.zeros((V, V), dtype=np.float32)\n\n    for sent in sentences:\n        tokens = [w for w in sent if w in word2idx]\n        for center_pos, center in enumerate(tokens):\n            ci = word2idx[center]\n            for offset in range(-window, window + 1):\n                if offset == 0:\n                    continue\n                ctx_pos = center_pos + offset\n                if 0 <= ctx_pos < len(tokens):\n                    cj = word2idx[tokens[ctx_pos]]\n                    matrix[ci, cj] += 1\n    return matrix\n\nvocab = [\"bank\", \"river\", \"money\", \"water\", \"loan\", \"cat\", \"dog\"]\nsentences = [\n    [\"the\", \"bank\", \"is\", \"on\", \"the\", \"river\"],\n    [\"the\", \"bank\", \"approved\", \"the\", \"loan\"],\n    [\"a\", \"cat\", \"and\", \"dog\", \"played\"],\n]\nco = build_cooccurrence(sentences, vocab, window=2)\nprint(co)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Positive Pointwise Mutual Information (PPMI)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Raw counts are dominated by frequent words like \"the\" that co-occur with everything. PMI corrects for frequency:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{PMI}(i, j) = \\log \\frac{P(i, j)}{P(i)\\, P(j)}"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A high PMI means words "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "i"}, {"type": "text", "text": " and "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "j"}, {"type": "text", "text": " co-occur more than chance would predict. PMI is negative for word pairs that rarely appear together, so PPMI floors it at zero:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{PPMI}(i, j) = \\max(0,\\, \\text{PMI}(i, j))"}}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "def ppmi(matrix):\n    \"\"\"Compute PPMI from a raw co-occurrence count matrix.\"\"\"\n    total = matrix.sum()\n    row_sums = matrix.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)   # P(i)\n    col_sums = matrix.sum(axis=0, keepdims=True)   # P(j)\n    # Add small epsilon to avoid log(0)\n    pmi = np.log((matrix * total) / (row_sums @ col_sums + 1e-9) + 1e-9)\n    return np.maximum(pmi, 0)   # zero out negatives\n\nppmi_matrix = ppmi(co)\nprint(ppmi_matrix)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dimensionality Reduction with SVD"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A V×V PPMI matrix for a 100 000-word vocabulary is 10 billion floats — too large to use directly. Truncated SVD (Singular Value Decomposition) factorises it into three smaller matrices and keeps only the top "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "d"}, {"type": "text", "text": " singular values:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "M \\approx U_d \\Sigma_d V_d^\\top"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The rows of "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "U_d"}, {"type": "text", "text": " are the d-dimensional word vectors. The truncation discards noise dimensions and compresses meaning into the directions with highest variance."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from sklearn.decomposition import TruncatedSVD\n\n# ppmi_matrix is V × V (sparse in practice, dense here for illustration)\nd = 50   # target embedding dimension\nsvd = TruncatedSVD(n_components=d, random_state=42)\nword_vectors = svd.fit_transform(ppmi_matrix)   # shape (V, d)\n\n# Cosine similarity between two words\ndef cosine(a, b):\n    return np.dot(a, b) / (np.linalg.norm(a) * np.linalg.norm(b) + 1e-9)\n\nvocab_list = vocab\nidx = {w: i for i, w in enumerate(vocab_list)}\n\nprint(cosine(word_vectors[idx[\"cat\"]], word_vectors[idx[\"dog\"]]))\nprint(cosine(word_vectors[idx[\"bank\"]], word_vectors[idx[\"river\"]]))"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Relationship to GloVe and Word2Vec"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Levy & Goldberg (2014) showed that Word2Vec with negative sampling implicitly factorises a shifted PMI matrix — the neural method and the count-based SVD approach are mathematically equivalent under certain conditions. GloVe makes this connection explicit by constructing the objective directly from co-occurrence counts."}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Method"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How it uses co-occurrence"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Reduction strategy"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "PPMI + SVD (LSA)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Global, explicit V×V matrix"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Truncated SVD"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GloVe"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Global, explicit V×V matrix"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Weighted least-squares (neural)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Word2Vec"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Local windows, implicit"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SGD on prediction objective (≈ shifted PMI factorisation)"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "LSA (Deerwester et al., 1990) applies SVD to a term-document matrix rather than a word-word co-occurrence matrix. The rows represent terms; columns represent documents. After SVD, documents with similar vocabulary end up close in the reduced space even if they share no exact keywords — a form of semantic matching."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\nfrom sklearn.decomposition import TruncatedSVD\nfrom sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import Normalizer\n\ncorpus = [\n    \"the cat sat on the mat\",\n    \"the dog lay on the rug\",\n    \"cats and dogs are pets\",\n    \"machine learning is about patterns in data\",\n    \"deep learning uses neural networks\",\n]\n\n# Build LSA pipeline: TF-IDF → SVD → L2 normalise\nlsa = make_pipeline(\n    TfidfVectorizer(),\n    TruncatedSVD(n_components=2, random_state=42),\n    Normalizer(copy=False),\n)\ndoc_vecs = lsa.fit_transform(corpus)   # shape (5, 2)\n\nimport numpy as np\n# Cosine similarity between doc 0 (cat/mat) and doc 1 (dog/rug)\nprint(np.dot(doc_vecs[0], doc_vecs[1]))   # high: semantically related\nprint(np.dot(doc_vecs[0], doc_vecs[3]))   # low: different topic"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "When to Use Count-Based Methods"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Small, domain-specific corpora"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": neural embeddings need millions of sentences to converge; PPMI+SVD can produce useful vectors from thousands."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Interpretability"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": singular vectors can be examined; specific dimensions sometimes correspond to identifiable semantic axes."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Document retrieval (LSA)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": query expansion and synonym matching without any labelled data."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Baseline comparisons"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": PPMI+SVD is fast to build and offers a strong zero-effort baseline before trying Word2Vec or BERT."}]}]}]}]}}